== Mitochondrial Hypotheses

=== WASF3-Mediated Supercomplex Disruption
<sec:wasf3-cascade>

*Certainty: 0.35.* WASF3 supercomplex disruption documented in cell models ‚ÄĒ Wang 2023 (@wang2023wasf3) showed that WASF3 overexpression in skeletal muscle cells disassembles mitochondrial respiratory supercomplexes (SC I/III/IV), reducing ETC efficiency by ~40%. WASF3 appears to act as a supercomplex assembly inhibitor ‚ÄĒ its upregulation prevents individual ETC complexes from organizing into functional supercomplexes, which are essential for efficient electron channelling (direct transfer of electrons from Complex I to Complex III within the supercomplex, minimizing electron leak and ROS production). HIF-1őĪ-driven WASF3 upregulation is mechanistic inference ‚ÄĒ HIF-1őĪ binds to hypoxia response elements in the WASF3 promoter under conditions of cellular hypoxia or pseudohypoxia (ROS-mediated prolyl hydroxylase inhibition). The HIF-1őĪ‚ÜíWASF3‚ÜíSC disruption pathway provides a mechanistic link between oxidative stress (HIF-1őĪ stabilization) and mitochondrial dysfunction (SC disassembly). No interventions have been tested in ME/CFS for WASF3 specifically.

==== Cascade: HIF-1őĪ ‚Üí WASF3 ‚Üí supercomplex disruption ‚Üí ATP deficit

*Cascade:*
- HIF-1őĪ stabilization (chronic ROS ‚Üí PHD inhibition, or genetic HIF1A variants ‚Üí constitutive activity)
- WASF3 transcriptional upregulation ‚Üí WASF3 protein at mitochondrial outer membrane
- Respiratory supercomplex (SC I/III/IV) assembly failure ‚Üí reduced electron channelling efficiency
- Increased electron leak at Complex I-III interface ‚Üí ROS (further stabilizes HIF-1őĪ ‚ÄĒ positive feedback)
- Reduced OXPHOS ATP yield + compensatory glycolysis (PDK1, LDH-A, GLUT1 upregulation)
- Lactate at rest, reduced maximal ATP output ‚Üí fatigue, PEM, the metabolic signature of ME/CFS


==== Step D1: HIF-1őĪ stabilization ‚Üí WASF3 upregulation (transcriptional trigger)

*Mechanism:* HIF-1őĪ is the master transcriptional regulator of the hypoxic response. Under normoxia, HIF-1őĪ is constitutively produced but immediately degraded (prolyl hydroxylase hydroxylates HIF-1őĪ ‚Üí pVHL ubiquitin ligase recognition ‚Üí proteasomal degradation). Under hypoxia or pseudohypoxia (ROS accumulation, succinate accumulation, fumarate accumulation ‚ÄĒ all inhibit prolyl hydroxylase), HIF-1őĪ escapes degradation ‚Üí translocates to nucleus ‚Üí dimerizes with HIF-1ő≤ ‚Üí binds hypoxia response elements (HREs) ‚Üí transcriptionally activates target genes including WASF3, PDK1, LDH-A, GLUT1, and VEGF.

*Probes for HIF-1őĪ‚ÜíWASF3 pathway:*
- *Dimethyl fumarate (DMF, 120--240 mg BID):* Activates Nrf2 ‚Üí Nrf2 binds antioxidant response elements (AREs) ‚Üí upregulates antioxidant enzymes (SOD, catalase, glutathione peroxidase) ‚Üí reduces ROS ‚Üí reduces ROS-mediated prolyl hydroxylase inhibition ‚Üí restores HIF-1őĪ degradation ‚Üí reduces WASF3 expression. Additionally, DMF directly inhibits HIF-1őĪ nuclear translocation (Nrf2 competes with HIF-1őĪ for CBP/p300 coactivators). If DMF improves exercise tolerance and reduces lactate ‚Üí HIF-1őĪ-driven WASF3 upregulation is present and rate-limiting. If DMF causes severe flushing ‚Üí mast cell hyper-reactivity (Pattern 3, @sec:side-effects-diagnostic) ‚ÄĒ pre-treat with aspirin (blocks PGD2-mediated flushing without affecting Nrf2 activation). If flushing is aspirin-preventable ‚Üí confirms PGD2-mediated MCAS subtype.
- *Vitamin C (500--2000 mg, timed with peak prolyl hydroxylase activity ‚ÄĒ circadian-optimized per ch14a):* Prolyl hydroxylase requires vitamin C as a cofactor. If timed vitamin C improves symptoms ‚Üí prolyl hydroxylase was cofactor-limited, and HIF-1őĪ stabilization was vitamin-C-reversible. Distinguishes cofactor deficiency (simple, nutritional) from ROS-mediated PHD inhibition (requires antioxidant intervention). If vitamin C + NAC works where vitamin C alone does not ‚Üí ROS is the dominant PHD inhibitor; the vitamin C provides cofactor, NAC scavenges the ROS that was inhibiting PHD.
- *If DMF AND vitamin C/NAC produce no improvement:* HIF-1őĪ stabilization is not the dominant mechanism of WASF3 upregulation. WASF3 may be regulated by: (a) genetic variants in the WASF3 promoter or 3'UTR (GWAS signal near WASF3 locus in ME/CFS ‚ÄĒ the DecodeME GWAS may implicate WASF3); (b) epigenetic regulation (WASF3 promoter methylation); or (c) non-HIF-1őĪ transcriptional regulators (NF-őļB, STAT3 ‚ÄĒ both activated by inflammatory cytokines, both have binding sites in the WASF3 promoter).

==== Step D2: Respiratory supercomplex assembly failure (structural mitochondrial defect)

*Mechanism:* SC I/III/IV forms in a specific stoichiometry (I:III‚āā:IV) that channels electrons directly from Complex I to Complex III within the lipid bilayer ‚ÄĒ no need for ubiquinone to diffuse electrons between complexes. This channelling increases electron transfer efficiency and reduces electron leak (ROS production). WASF3 disrupts this assembly ‚Üí Complex I and III must rely on ubiquinone-mediated electron transfer (slower, leakier) ‚Üí electrons escape at the I-III interface ‚Üí superoxide production ‚Üí oxidative stress. The result: reduced ATP yield per NADH (~2.5 ATP ‚Üí ~1.5 ATP) and increased ROS per unit of oxygen consumed.

*Probes for supercomplex disruption:*
- *CoQ10 (ubiquinone, 100--300 mg) + NADH (5--20 mg):* CoQ10 shuttles electrons from Complex I/II to Complex III. In SC disruption, CoQ10 + NADH flooding provides supraphysiological substrate to compensate for reduced channelling efficiency ‚ÄĒ more electrons reach Complex III because there is more electron carrier in the membrane. If CoQ10 + NADH dramatically improves symptoms (‚Č•50% improvement) ‚Üí SC disruption is partial ‚ÄĒ the remaining supercomplexes can handle increased electron flux. If CoQ10 + NADH produces only modest benefit (10--20%) ‚Üí SC disruption is severe ‚ÄĒ substrate flooding cannot overcome the assembly defect; mitochondria need turnover, not cofactor supplementation. If CoQ10 + NADH produces WORSENING ‚Üí electron leak at Complex I-III interface increases when substrate flux is increased ‚Üí more ROS production ‚Üí oxidative damage. The direction of CoQ10 response IS the SC disruption severity marker.
- *L-carnitine (500--1000 mg):* Enhances fatty acid oxidation ‚Üí generates FADH‚āā (enters at Complex II, electron-transferring flavoprotein ‚Üí ubiquinone ‚Üí Complex III). If L-carnitine improves symptoms where CoQ10 does NOT ‚Üí Complex I is the specific bottleneck, and bypassing it via Complex II (FADH‚āā from FAO) restores electron flux. The SC disruption is Complex I-specific ‚ÄĒ Complex II-containing supercomplexes are intact.
- *MitoQ (mitoquinone, 5--10 mg):* Ubiquinone conjugated to triphenylphosphonium cation ‚Üí accumulates 100--1000√ó in mitochondrial matrix (driven by membrane potential). More potent than CoQ10. If MitoQ works where CoQ10 does NOT ‚Üí the ubiquinone pool in the mitochondrial membrane is inaccessible to oral CoQ10 (poor bioavailability) but MitoQ reaches the matrix. MitoQ response confirms ubiquinone deficiency at the mitochondrial level.

==== Step D3: Reduced OXPHOS ATP yield ‚Üí energy deficit

*Mechanism:* Even with adequate substrate delivery and ETC function, if SC disruption reduces electron channelling efficiency, the ATP yield per NADH is reduced. The result: more oxygen consumed per ATP produced (reduced P/O ratio), more substrate consumed per ATP, and more ROS produced. This is the biochemical signature of mitochondrial inefficiency ‚ÄĒ not failure, but reduced efficiency.

*Probes for compensating for reduced ATP yield:*
- *Creatine monohydrate (5 g/day):* Phosphocreatine buffer ‚ÄĒ provides rapid ATP regeneration from phosphocreatine + ADP ‚Üí creatine + ATP via creatine kinase. Bypasses ETC entirely for short-term ATP buffering. If creatine improves exercise tolerance ‚Üí ATP buffering is insufficient for the reduced ATP production rate. If creatine produces NO improvement ‚Üí the ATP deficit is too large for buffering to compensate, OR the bottleneck is at ATP utilization (creatine already saturating the creatine kinase system).
- *D-ribose (5--15 g/day):* Pentose sugar essential for ATP synthesis (ribose ‚Üí PRPP ‚Üí purine synthesis ‚Üí ATP). NOT an energy source ‚ÄĒ it provides the ribose backbone for ATP. If D-ribose improves symptoms ‚Üí ATP synthesis capacity is limited by ribose availability (the de novo purine synthesis pathway is rate-limiting). If D-ribose has no effect ‚Üí the bottleneck is in the ETC or mitochondrial membrane, not in nucleotide synthesis.
- *NMN/NR (NAD‚Āļ precursors):* If SC disruption also impairs Complex I NADH oxidation ‚Üí NADH accumulates, NAD‚Āļ is depleted, and NAD‚Āļ supplementation may restore the NAD‚Āļ/NADH ratio. If NMN/NR + CoQ10 produces benefit where either alone does not ‚Üí dual mitochondrial lesion: SC disruption (CoQ10-dependent) AND NAD‚Āļ deficiency (NMN/NR-dependent). The NAD‚Āļ deficiency is compounding the SC disruption.

*Consequence:* The WASF3 cascade is the only mitochondrial hypothesis in the chapter that links a specific genetic/protein-level defect (WASF3 overexpression) to a specific structural mitochondrial defect (SC disassembly) to measurable metabolic consequences (reduced ATP yield, increased ROS). The diagnostic sequence: (1) CoQ10 ¬Ī response magnitude ‚Üí severity of SC disruption; (2) DMF response ‚Üí HIF-1őĪ is the transcriptional driver; (3) vitamin C/NAC response ‚Üí ROS-mediated PHD inhibition vs. cofactor deficiency; (4) L-carnitine response ‚Üí Complex I-specific vs. global SC disruption; (5) NMN/NR response ‚Üí compounding NAD‚Āļ deficiency. The DecodeME GWAS results (if WASF3 locus is implicated) would validate this cascade at the genetic level ‚ÄĒ if WASF3 variants are associated with ME/CFS, this cascade transitions from 0.35 to 0.50+ certainty.
*Origin:* mechanistic-pathway-tracing.

=== PDH Inhibition / Pyruvate Dehydrogenase
<sec:pdh-cascade>

*Certainty: 0.40.* PDK-driven PDH inhibition is mechanistically well-grounded in cytokine biology ‚ÄĒ PDK1 and PDK4 are transcriptionally upregulated by PPARőĪ and HIF-1őĪ in response to inflammatory cytokines, fasting, and hypoxia. PDH is the gatekeeper enzyme: it converts pyruvate (from glycolysis) to acetyl-CoA (which enters the TCA cycle). When PDH is phosphorylated by PDK, pyruvate cannot enter the TCA cycle ‚Üí pyruvate accumulates ‚Üí converted to lactate by lactate dehydrogenase ‚Üí lactate exits the cell ‚Üí systemic lactate elevation at low workloads. The consequence: the muscle is forced into anaerobic metabolism at exertion levels far below the anaerobic threshold of a healthy person. ~83% of glucose-derived ATP depends on PDH-mediated pyruvate entry to TCA ‚ÄĒ with PDH blocked, glucose becomes an inefficient fuel. This is the biochemical explanation for the PEM phenomenon: exertion produces lactate at workloads that should be aerobic, and ATP yield per glucose molecule drops from ~36 to ~2 (glycolysis only). The 2-day CPET finding (reduced VO‚āāpeak and increased lactate on Day 2) is consistent with PDH inhibition that worsens with repeated exertion.

==== Cascade: Cytokines ‚Üí PDK ‚Üí PDH block ‚Üí lactate + energy deficit

*Cascade:*
- Inflammatory cytokines (TNF-őĪ, IL-1ő≤, IFN-ő≥) ‚Üí PDK1/PDK4 upregulation (HIF-1őĪ, PPARőĪ)
- PDK phosphorylates PDH E1őĪ at Ser293 ‚Üí PDH inactivation ‚Üí pyruvate blocked from TCA
- Glycolytic-ETC uncoupling ‚Üí three arms:
- (a) lactate accumulation ‚Üí muscle fatigue, burning, PEM at low workloads
- (b) reduced acetyl-CoA ‚Üí reduced TCA flux ‚Üí reduced ATP yield ‚Üí energy deficit
- (c) compensatory fatty acid oxidation ‚Üí lipid dependence ‚Üí if ő≤-oxidation impaired ‚Üí dual metabolic blockade


==== Step E1: PDK upregulation (inflammatory trigger)

*Probe:* LDN (0.5--4.5 mg, anti-inflammatory). LDN reduces TLR4-mediated cytokine production ‚Üí reduces PDK transcriptional drive.

*If LDN reduces exertional lactate (measurable with handheld lactate meter at standardized submaximal workload):* Inflammatory PDK activation is present and rate-limiting ‚ÄĒ reducing inflammation restores PDH function. This is strong evidence for cytokine-driven metabolic blockade. The lactate measurement is objective ‚ÄĒ it does not rely on subjective symptom report.

*If LDN reduces symptoms but lactate is unchanged:* LDN's benefit is not through PDH restoration ‚ÄĒ it is through anti-neuroinflammatory, TRPM3, or endorphin mechanisms independent of muscle metabolism. The lactate dissociation distinguishes metabolic from neurological LDN benefit.

*If LDN does NOT reduce lactate:* PDK may be induced by non-TLR4 inflammatory pathways (TNF-őĪ from non-TLR4 sources, direct HIF-1őĪ stabilization from ROS/hypoxia independent of inflammation), or PDH is inhibited by mechanisms beyond PDK (PDH phosphatase inhibition, thiamine deficiency, or genetic PDH variants).

==== Step E2: PDH phosphorylation ‚ÄĒ enzymatic block (the enzyme level)

*Probes for restoring PDH activity:*
- *Dichloroacetate (DCA, 12.5--25 mg/kg/day, investigational in ME/CFS):* PDK inhibitor ‚ÄĒ directly blocks the kinase that phosphorylates and inactivates PDH. DCA restores PDH activity regardless of upstream cytokine drive. If DCA dramatically reduces lactate and improves exercise tolerance ‚Üí PDH phosphorylation IS the rate-limiting metabolic step. DCA is the highest-specificity probe for PDH in this chapter. CAUTION: DCA causes reversible peripheral neuropathy at cumulative doses >30 g ‚ÄĒ limit trial duration; monitor nerve conduction. DCA is not approved for ME/CFS ‚ÄĒ requires off-label prescription or clinical trial access.
- *Thiamine (B1, 100--900 mg/day, IV or oral):* Essential cofactor for PDH (thiamine pyrophosphate is the prosthetic group of PDH E1). If thiamine works ‚Üí PDH cofactor deficiency. Simple, reversible, nutritional ‚ÄĒ the most accessible PDH probe. Distinguish: thiamine deficiency vs. PDK-driven phosphorylation. If LDN does NOT reduce lactate but thiamine DOES ‚Üí PDH inhibition is from cofactor deficiency, not PDK-mediated phosphorylation. If thiamine works and LDN works ‚Üí dual mechanism: inflammatory PDK activation + thiamine deficiency (common in SIBO, gut dysbiosis).
- *Alpha-lipoic acid (300--600 mg BID):* Antioxidant that also serves as a PDH cofactor and reduces PDK expression. If ALA works ‚Üí oxidative stress drives PDK expression, and antioxidant + cofactor support restores PDH.
- *Magnesium (400--800 mg, IV or oral):* Mg¬≤‚Āļ is a PDH phosphatase cofactor ‚ÄĒ PDH phosphatase requires Mg¬≤‚Āļ to dephosphorylate and activate PDH. If IV magnesium improves exercise tolerance ‚Üí Mg¬≤‚Āļ deficiency prevented PDH dephosphorylation. The PDH enzyme is phosphorylated (PDK active) AND cannot be dephosphorylated (PDH phosphatase Mg¬≤‚Āļ-deficient).
