- Structural mitochondrial damage ‚Üí progressive loss of oxidative capacity ‚Üí PEM, Day 2 CPET decline


==== Step F1: Capillary hypoperfusion (vascular trigger ‚ÄĒ upstream of ionic cascade)

*Mechanism:* The initial event is impaired oxygen delivery to working muscle. This can be from: (a) endothelial dysfunction ‚ÄĒ GPCR AAb (ő≤2-AR, M2/M4) impair endothelium-dependent vasodilation ‚Üí exercise hyperemia fails ‚Üí muscle receives less blood during exertion; (b) microclots ‚ÄĒ amyloid fibrin(ogen) microclots (Pretorius 2021) obstruct capillaries ‚Üí reduced functional capillary density; (c) RBC deformability loss ‚ÄĒ stiff erythrocytes cannot pass through capillaries smaller than their diameter ‚Üí impaired microvascular flow; (d) autonomic failure ‚ÄĒ impaired sympathetic vasoconstriction in non-exercising muscle beds + impaired vasodilation in exercising muscle ‚Üí blood flow misdistribution.

*Probes for the vascular trigger:*
- *Pyridostigmine (30--60 mg):* Enhances cardiac preload and output ‚Üí increases total blood flow ‚Üí more oxygen delivery to all tissues @Joseph2022pyridostigmine. If pyridostigmine improves VO‚āāpeak at CPET ‚Üí the delivery deficit is preload/cardiac output-mediated. If pyridostigmine does NOT improve VO‚āāpeak ‚Üí the delivery deficit is microvascular (capillary-level obstruction, not macro-level flow).
- *Midodrine (2.5--10 mg):* Increases perfusion pressure. If midodrine improves exercise tolerance ‚Üí perfusion pressure was insufficient to overcome capillary resistance. If midodrine does NOT improve ‚Üí perfusion pressure is not the bottleneck.
- *Compression garments (abdominal + leg):* Reduce venous pooling ‚Üí maintain preload without drugs. If compression improves exercise tolerance ‚Üí venous pooling contributes to delivery deficit.
- *Pyridostigmine + midodrine + compression:* If the combination improves VO‚āāpeak where any single intervention does not ‚Üí multi-level delivery deficit: preload, perfusion pressure, and venous pooling are all contributing.
- *If NO delivery intervention improves VO‚āāpeak:* The bottleneck is NOT oxygen delivery ‚ÄĒ it is mitochondrial oxygen utilization. Oxygen is reaching the mitochondria, but the mitochondria cannot use it. Proceed to mitochondrial-level probes (CoQ10, L-carnitine, creatine).

==== Step F2: Intracellular Na‚Āļ overload (ionic consequence of ischemia)

*Mechanism:* Ischemic muscle shifts to anaerobic glycolysis ‚Üí lactic acid production ‚Üí intracellular pH drops. The Na‚Āļ/H‚Āļ exchanger (NHE1) is activated by low pH ‚ÄĒ it extrudes one H‚Āļ in exchange for one Na‚Āļ ‚Üí normalizes pH at the cost of Na‚Āļ accumulation inside the cell. This is protective in acute ischemia (prevents acid-induced protein denaturation) but pathological in repeated ischemia-reperfusion (chronic Na‚Āļ overload).

*Probes for the Na‚Āļ overload step:*
- *MDC002/Mitodicure (investigational, NHE1 inhibitor + NCLX activator):* Blocks NHE1 (prevents Na‚Āļ entry) and activates the mitochondrial Na‚Āļ/Ca¬≤‚Āļ/Li‚Āļ exchanger (NCLX, extrudes mitochondrial Ca¬≤‚Āļ). If MDC002 improves PEM recovery and CPET Day 2 performance in clinical trials ‚Üí the Na‚Āļ‚ÜíCa¬≤‚Āļ cascade is causally driving mitochondrial damage. Currently investigational ‚ÄĒ no clinical trial results in ME/CFS as of writing.
- *Amiloride (NHE inhibitor, 5--10 mg):* Weak NHE1 inhibitor at clinical doses (more potent at NHE2/NHE3 in kidney). If amiloride improves exercise tolerance ‚Üí NHE1 is rate-limiting and even weak inhibition produces benefit. This is a low-certainty, high-risk probe (electrolyte disturbances) ‚ÄĒ only informative if the result is dramatic.
- *Ranolazine (late Na‚Āļ current inhibitor, 500--1000 mg BID):* Blocks the late inward Na‚Āļ current (late INa) in cardiac and skeletal muscle, reducing intracellular Na‚Āļ. Approved for angina. If ranolazine improves PEM ‚Üí the Na‚Āļ overload is from late INa channels (not just NHE1) ‚ÄĒ broader Na‚Āļ dysregulation. If ranolazine null ‚Üí NHE1 is the dominant Na‚Āļ entry pathway, not late INa.

==== Step F3: NCX1 reverse mode ‚Üí mitochondrial Ca¬≤‚Āļ overload (the tipping point)

*Mechanism:* NCX1 normally operates in forward mode (3 Na‚Āļ in, 1 Ca¬≤‚Āļ out ‚ÄĒ uses the Na‚Āļ gradient to extrude Ca¬≤‚Āļ). When intracellular Na‚Āļ is very high (from NHE1 activity), the Na‚Āļ gradient collapses. NCX1 reverses: it imports Ca¬≤‚Āļ into the cell while extruding Na‚Āļ. The result is cytosolic Ca¬≤‚Āļ overload. Mitochondria buffer cytosolic Ca¬≤‚Āļ by taking it up through the mitochondrial calcium uniporter (MCU) ‚ÄĒ but chronic Ca¬≤‚Āļ uptake ‚Üí mitochondrial Ca¬≤‚Āļ overload ‚Üí mPTP opening ‚Üí mitochondrial depolarization and structural damage.

*Probes for the NCX1‚Üímitochondrial Ca¬≤‚Āļ step:*
- *Magnesium (IV or high-dose oral, 400--800 mg):* Mg¬≤‚Āļ is a physiological NMDA receptor antagonist and NCX modulator ‚ÄĒ high Mg¬≤‚Āļ competes with Ca¬≤‚Āļ at multiple sites. If IV magnesium improves PEM recovery ‚Üí the Ca¬≤‚Āļ overload is Mg¬≤‚Āļ-suppressible.
- *Dantrolene (ryanodine receptor antagonist, 25--50 mg):* Blocks Ca¬≤‚Āļ release from sarcoplasmic reticulum through RyR1 channels in skeletal muscle. If dantrolene improves PEM ‚Üí the Ca¬≤‚Āļ overload is from SR Ca¬≤‚Āļ release (RyR1 leak) + NCX1 reverse mode ‚ÄĒ dual-source Ca¬≤‚Āļ pathology. If dantrolene null ‚Üí NCX1 is the sole Ca¬≤‚Āļ source.
- *If both magnesium AND MDC002 work:* The Ca¬≤‚Āļ overload has multiple entry pathways ‚ÄĒ intervention at the NHE1 level (MDC002) and the Mg¬≤‚Āļ-sensitive level both reduce Ca¬≤‚Āļ overload. Consistent with the full NHE1‚ÜíNCX1‚Üímitochondrial Ca¬≤‚Āļ cascade as causal.

==== Step F4: Mitochondrial structural damage ‚Üí mitophagy impairment

*Mechanism:* Chronically damaged mitochondria with open mPTP are targets for mitophagy (selective autophagy of mitochondria). PINK1 accumulates on depolarized mitochondria ‚Üí recruits Parkin ‚Üí ubiquitination ‚Üí autophagosome engulfment ‚Üí lysosomal degradation. In ME/CFS, mTORC1 is hypothesized to be overactive (driven by chronic low-grade inflammation and insulin signaling) ‚Üí mTORC1 inhibits autophagy initiation (ULK1 phosphorylation) ‚Üí damaged mitochondria accumulate because they cannot be cleared.

*Probes for the mitophagy step:*
- *Rapamycin (1--3 mg/week, mTORC1 inhibitor):* Inhibits mTORC1 ‚Üí disinhibits autophagy ‚Üí allows clearance of damaged mitochondria. If rapamycin improves exercise tolerance over weeks ‚Üí damaged mitochondria were accumulating and their clearance was mTORC1-suppressed. Onset latency: improvement at 2--4 weeks ‚Üí mitophagy requires time to clear the backlog of damaged mitochondria.
- *Urolithin A (500--1000 mg/day, mitophagy activator):* Activates mitophagy through PINK1/Parkin-independent pathway. If urolithin A works where rapamycin does NOT ‚Üí the mitophagy defect is not mTORC1-mediated ‚ÄĒ it is at the PINK1/Parkin recognition step, or the lysosomal degradation capacity is preserved but the signal to initiate mitophagy is absent. Urolithin A bypasses the initiation signal.
- *NAC + CoQ10 (antioxidant support):* If NAC + CoQ10 improves exercise tolerance but rapamycin does NOT ‚Üí the mitochondrial damage is from ROS-mediated functional impairment (electron leak), not structural damage requiring clearance. The mitochondria can be rescued with antioxidants ‚ÄĒ they do not need to be replaced.
- *Mitochondrial supplement worsening (CoQ10, carnitine worsen symptoms):* If CoQ10 worsens ‚Üí Complex III is blocked ‚ÄĒ electrons back up, producing superoxide (Pattern 5, @sec:side-effects-diagnostic). If carnitine worsens ‚Üí ő≤-oxidation overload produces lipid peroxides in glutathione-depleted cells (Pattern 5). Worsening patterns localize WHICH ETC complex or FAO step is the bottleneck.

*Consequence:* The AIMM cascade traces the full ischemia‚Üíion‚Üímitochondrial damage pathway in four distinguishable steps: vascular trigger (pyridostigmine, midodrine, compression), NHE1-mediated Na‚Āļ overload (MDC002, amiloride, ranolazine), NCX1-mediated Ca¬≤‚Āļ overload (magnesium, dantrolene), and mitophagy failure (rapamycin, urolithin A, NAC+CoQ10). Each step has a specific probe; the pattern of which probe works localizes how far down the cascade the lesion has progressed. A patient who responds to pyridostigmine (delivery) but not rapamycin (mitophagy) has early-stage AIMM ‚ÄĒ the vascular trigger is rate-limiting and mitochondrial damage is reversible. A patient who responds to rapamycin but not pyridostigmine has late-stage AIMM ‚ÄĒ mitochondrial damage has accumulated beyond what delivery improvement can compensate for, and mitophagy restoration is needed to clear the backlog. The PEM phenotype in AIMM: if pyridostigmine reduces PEM duration by 50% but rapamycin reduces it by 80% ‚Üí both delivery AND clearance are rate-limiting, with clearance being the dominant bottleneck. The AIMM cascade is the mechanistic bridge between the vascular hypothesis and the mitochondrial hypothesis ‚ÄĒ it explains how impaired blood flow becomes impaired mitochondrial function through a specific ionic cascade.
